## Migration: `TimedExecutor` — Thread.Abort to Cooperative Cancellation

### Pattern: **Timeout enforcement**

Your code uses `Thread.Abort` to kill a thread that exceeds a deadline. In .NET 6+, `Thread.Abort` throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` and `Thread.ResetAbort` is a no-op. You must switch to cooperative cancellation.

### What's wrong with the original code on .NET 8

| API | .NET 8 behavior |
|-----|-----------------|
| `thread.Abort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Throws `PlatformNotSupportedException` |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | Never thrown — dead code |

---

### Migrated code

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        // Task.Run moves the work to the thread pool
        var task = Task.Run(work);

        try
        {
            // Wait with a timeout — throws TimeoutException on expiry
            if (task.Wait(timeout))
            {
                // Task completed within the deadline
                return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
            }

            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae) when (ae.InnerExceptions.Count == 1)
        {
            // Unwrap single-exception AggregateException to match
            // the original behavior of throwing AggregateException(inner)
            throw new AggregateException(ae.InnerException!);
        }
    }
}
```

> **⚠️ Critical caveat:** This is a *minimal behavioral port* — the work continues running in the background after timeout, just like abandoning a thread. Read on for the proper cooperative version.

---

### Recommended version (cooperative cancellation)

This is the correct .NET 8 approach — the work **actually stops** on timeout:

```csharp
public class TimedExecutor
{
    public T ExecuteWithTimeout<T>(Func<CancellationToken, T> work, TimeSpan timeout)
    {
        using var cts = new CancellationTokenSource(timeout);

        try
        {
            var task = Task.Run(() => work(cts.Token), cts.Token);
            return task.GetAwaiter().GetResult();
        }
        catch (OperationCanceledException) when (cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
        catch (AggregateException ae)
            when (ae.InnerException is OperationCanceledException
                  && cts.IsCancellationRequested)
        {
            throw new TimeoutException(
                $"Operation exceeded {timeout.TotalSeconds}s timeout");
        }
    }
}
```

**Callers must update their lambdas** to accept and check the token:

```csharp
// BEFORE (.NET Framework)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    () => ExpensiveCalculation(),
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));

// AFTER (.NET 8)
var result = executor.ExecuteWithTimeout(
    ct =>
    {
        for (int i = 0; i < 1_000_000; i++)
        {
            ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested(); // checkpoint
            DoPartialWork(i);
        }
        return finalResult;
    },
    TimeSpan.FromSeconds(5));
```

---

### Key pitfalls

| Pitfall | Why it matters |
|---------|---------------|
| **Work doesn't actually stop** | Unlike `Thread.Abort`, cancellation is *cooperative*. If your lambda never checks the token, it runs to completion even after timeout. Insert `ct.ThrowIfCancellationRequested()` at regular checkpoints. |
| **Forgetting `using` on `CancellationTokenSource`** | `CTS` owns an internal timer when constructed with a timeout. Not disposing it leaks the timer. |
| **Swallowing `OperationCanceledException`** | Let it propagate — only catch at the top-level orchestration point (here, to convert it to `TimeoutException`). |
| **Not passing the token through the full call chain** | If your work calls async APIs or library methods, pass `ct` all the way down. One method that ignores the token blocks cancellation. |
| **`Thread.Sleep` inside the work** | `Thread.Sleep` ignores cancellation. Replace with `ct.WaitHandle.WaitOne(ms)` or `Task.Delay(ms, ct).Wait(ct)`. |
| **Uncooperative third-party code** | If you can't modify the work to check a token, the *only* reliable kill mechanism is `Process.Kill` on a child process. A fire-and-forget `Task.Run` without token checks will leak the work. |

---

### API mapping summary

| .NET Framework | .NET 8 replacement |
|---|---|
| `thread.Abort()` | `cts.Cancel()` (or auto-cancel via `CTS(timeout)`) |
| `catch (ThreadAbortException)` | `catch (OperationCanceledException)` |
| `Thread.ResetAbort()` | Check `token.IsCancellationRequested` and decide whether to continue |
| `thread.Join(timeout)` | `task.Wait(timeout)` or `await task.WaitAsync(ct)` |
